  "text": "A study conducted in Taiwan evaluated SGA (defined as term low birth weight) and preterm delivery and included first-parity, singleton births born during 1994-1996 in 14 chlorinated municipalities (n = 10,007) served primarily by surface water supplies and 14 nonchlorinating municipalities (n = 8,018) served primarily by groundwater supplies [CITATION_1] . Municipalities were matched based on their urbanization level. Odds ratios were adjusted for maternal age, martial status, maternal education, and sex of the infant, which were obtained from the birth certificates. Births exposed to chlorinated supplies had a higher rate of preterm birth (odds ratio [OR] = 1.34, 95% CI: 1.1, 1.6) but a lower rate for SGA (OR = 0.90, 95% CI: 0.7, 1.1). The authors of the study note that because these municipalities were rural, it was unlikely that women drank bottled water or any water from sources other than the home.",
